# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: auregnais
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] These features typically occur in the speech of older people.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] Many aspects of Acadian French (vocabulary and "trill r", etc.) are still common in rural areas in the southwest of France.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] Speakers of Metropolitan French and even of other Canadian varieties of French sometimes have difficulty understanding Acadian French.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] Within North America, its closest relative is Louisiana French spoken in Southern Louisiana since both were born out of the same population that were affected during the Expulsion of the Acadians.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] See also Chiac, a variety with strong English influence, and St.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] Marys Bay French, a distinct variety of Acadian French spoken around Clare, Tusket, Nova Scotia and also Moncton, New Brunswick.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] For example, *mercredi* ('Wednesday') is *mercordi*, and *pauvreté* ('poverty') is *pauveurté*.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] *Je* (the pronoun 'I') is frequently pronounced *euj* and *Le* is frequently pronounced *eul*.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] In words, "re" is often pronounced "er".
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] Yves Cormier's *Dictionnaire du français acadien* (ComiersAcad) includes the majority of Acadian regionalisms.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] From a syntactic point of view, a major feature is the use of *je* for the first-person singular and plural; the same phenomenon takes place with *i* for the third persons.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] Acadian still differentiates the *vous* form from the *tu* form.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] The following words and expressions are most commonly restricted to Acadian French south of the Miramichi River, but some are also used north of the Miramichi River and in Quebec French (also known as Québécois) or Joual for the Montreal version of Quebec French.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] The Miramichi line is an isogloss separating South Acadian (archaic or "true" Acadian) from the Canadian French dialects to the north, North Acadian, Brayon (Madawaskan) and Quebec French (Laurentian French).
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] Geddes (1908), the oldest authority on any variety of French spoken in Northern Acadia, records of the morphosyntactic characteristics of "true" Acadian spoken in the South and adjacent islands to the West.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] Marys Bay French, a conservative dialect of Acadian French spoken in the St.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] Marys Bay, Nova Scotia region, is notable for maintaining use of the *passé simple* in spoken conversation.
[src:auregnais/acadian-french] In most modern dialects of French, the tense is only used in formal writing and speech.
[src:auregnais/african-french] In each of the Francophone African countries, French is spoken with local variations in pronunciation and vocabulary.
[src:auregnais/african-french] French proficiency in African countries according to the Organisation internationale de la Francophonie (OIF).
[src:auregnais/african-french] The French variety spoken by Berbers and Maghrebis in North-west Africa (see Maghreb French), which has about 33 million first and second language speakers in 2018.
[src:auregnais/african-french] The French variety spoken in the Comoro Islands (the Comoros and Mayotte) and Madagascar, which have 5.6 million first and second language speakers in 2018.
[src:auregnais/african-french] The French variety spoken by Creoles in the Mascarene Islands (Mauritius and Réunion) and Seychelles, which has around 1.75 million first and second language speakers in 2018.
[src:auregnais/african-french] The French spoken in this region is not to be confused with the French-based creole languages, which are also spoken in the area.
[src:auregnais/african-french] The French variety spoken in Djibouti in the Horn of Africa, which has about 0.5 million first and second language speakers in 2018.
[src:auregnais/african-french] All the African French varieties differ from Standard French, both in terms of pronunciation and vocabulary, but the formal African French used in education, media and legal documents is based on standard French vocabulary.
[src:auregnais/african-french] In the colonial period, a vernacular form of creole French known as *Petit nègre* ("little negro") was also present in West Africa.
[src:auregnais/african-french] The term has since, however, become a pejorative term for "poorly spoken" African French.
[src:auregnais/african-french] In Angola, French is spoken in Angola especially Cabinda, particularly in the northern regions.
[src:auregnais/african-french] While Portuguese is the official language, French is understood and spoken, especially among the Kongo people in the north and by Angolans with French ancestry.
[src:auregnais/african-french] It's also one of the foreign languages taught in schools with 90% speak French from neighboring DR Congo as a legacy of Belgian colonial rule which established as Belgium's private colony of Francophone Africa until its independence on 30 June 1960.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Code-switching, or the alternation of languages within a single conversation, takes place in both DR Congo and Senegal, the former having four "national" languages – Ciluba, Kikongo, Lingala, and Swahili – which are in a permanent opposition to French.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Code-switching has been studied since colonial times by different institutions of linguistics.
[src:auregnais/african-french] The omnipresence of local languages in Francophone African countries – along with insufficiencies in education – has given birth to a new linguistic concept: *le petit français*.
[src:auregnais/african-french] *Le petit français* is the result of a superposition of the structure of a local language with a narrowed lexical knowledge of French.
[src:auregnais/african-french] The specific structures, though very different, are juxtaposed, marking the beginning of the creolization process.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Some African countries such as Algeria intermittently attempted to remove the use of French; it was removed as an official language in Mali, Burkina Faso, and Niger in 2023, 2024, and 2025 respectively.
[src:auregnais/african-french] In the urban areas of Francophone Africa, another type of French has emerged: *Français populaire africain* ("Popular African French") or FPA.
[src:auregnais/african-french] It is used in the entirety of Sub-Saharan Africa, but especially in cities such as Abidjan, Côte d'Ivoire; Cotonou, Benin; Dakar, Senegal; Lomé, Togo; and Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso.
[src:auregnais/african-french] However, FPA has begun to emerge as a second language among the upper class.
[src:auregnais/african-french] It has also become a symbol of social acceptance.
[src:auregnais/african-french] FPA can be seen as a progressive evolution of Ivorian French.
[src:auregnais/african-french] After diffusing out of Côte d'Ivoire, it became Africanized under the influence of young Africans (often students) and cinema, drama, and dance.
[src:auregnais/african-french] FPA has its own grammatical rules and lexicon.
[src:auregnais/african-french] For example, "*Il ou elle peut me tuer!*" or "*Il ou elle peut me dja!*" can either mean "This person annoys me very much (literally he or she is annoying me to death)" or "I'm dying (out of love) for him/her" depending on the circumstances.
[src:auregnais/african-french] FPA is mainly composed of metaphors and images taken from African languages.
[src:auregnais/african-french] For example, the upper social class is called "*les en-haut d'en-haut*" (the above from above) or "*les môgôs puissants*" (the powerful môgôs).
[src:auregnais/african-french] Pronunciation in the many varieties of African French can be quite varied.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Pronunciation of the letters ⟨d⟩, ⟨t⟩, ⟨l⟩ and ⟨l⟩ may also vary, and intonation may differ from standard French.
[src:auregnais/african-french] According to some estimates, French is spoken by 75 to 99 percent of Abidjan's population, either alone or alongside indigenous African languages.
[src:auregnais/african-french] There are three sorts of French spoken in Abidjan.
[src:auregnais/african-french] A formal French is spoken by the educated classes.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Finally, an Abidjan French slang called ***Nouchi*** has evolved from an ethnically neutral lingua franca among uneducated youth into a creole language with a distinct grammar.
[src:auregnais/african-french] New words often appear in *Nouchi* and then make their way into colloquial Abidjan French after some time.
[src:auregnais/african-french] As of 2012, a crowdsourced dictionary of *Nouchi* was being written using mobile phones.
[src:auregnais/african-french] When speaking in a formal context, or when meeting French speakers from outside Côte d'Ivoire, Abidjan speakers would replace these local words with the French standard words *une fille*, *un restaurant* or *une cantine*, *un copain*, *battre* and *l'argent* respectively.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Note that some local words are used across several African countries.
[src:auregnais/african-french] For example, *chicotter* is attested not only in Côte d'Ivoire but also in Senegal, Mali, Niger, Burkina Faso, Chad, the Central African Republic, Benin, Togo and the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
[src:auregnais/african-french] As already mentioned, these local words range from slang to formal usage, and their use therefore varies depending on the context.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Another unique, identifiable feature of Ivorian French is the use of the phrase *n'avoir qu'à + infinitif* which, translated into English, roughly means, *to have only to + infinitive*.
[src:auregnais/african-french] The phrase is often used in linguistic contexts of expressing a wish or creating hypotheticals.
[src:auregnais/african-french] This original Ivorian phrase is generally used across the Côte d'Ivoire's population; children, uneducated adults, and educated adults all using the phrase relatively equally.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Often in written speech, the phrase is written as *Ils non cas essayer de voir* rather than *Ils n'ont qu'à essayer de voir*.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Many characteristics of Ivorian/Abidjan French differ from "standard" French found in France.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Many of the linguistic evolutions are from the influences of native African languages spoken within the Côte d'Ivoire and make Abidjan French a distinct dialect of French.
[src:auregnais/african-french] There are also, to a certain degree, rhythmic speaking patterns in Ivorian French that are influenced by native languages.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Angola has had a historical and cultural connection with France, particularly through its colonial past and subsequent economic and political relationships with other countries including Francophone Africa which had been colonized as former French colonies from Paris.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Without being an official language, French is frequently used in government, workplaces, and education.
[src:auregnais/african-french] French is the default language for work in several sectors.
[src:auregnais/african-french] In a 2007 study set in the city of Mostaganem, it was shown that French and Arabic were the two functional languages of banking.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Technical work (accounting, financial analysis, management) is also frequently done in French.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Documents, forms, and posters are often in both French and Arabic.
[src:auregnais/african-french] The usage of French among the Algerian population is different depending on social situations.
[src:auregnais/african-french] French is the sole official language in Benin.
[src:auregnais/african-french] In 2014, over 4 million Beninese citizens spoke French (around 40% of the population).
[src:auregnais/african-french] Fongbe is the other widely spoken language of Benin.
[src:auregnais/african-french] It is natural to hear both languages blending, either through loan words or code-switching.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Few academic sources exist surrounding the particularisms of Beninese French.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Nevertheless, it is evident that Beninese French has adapted the meanings of several French terms over time, such as: *seconder* (to have relations with a second woman, from the French *second -* second), *doigter* (to show the way, from the French *doigt* - finger).
[src:auregnais/african-french] French is the language of administration, education, and business in Burkina Faso and was the *de jure* official language until a constitutional change in 2024.
[src:auregnais/african-french] While spoken fluently only by about a quarter of the population, French has progressively become a native language among urban populations since the late 20th century, notably in the cities of Ouagadougou, Bobo-Dioulasso, and Banfora.
[src:auregnais/african-french] By 2010, about 10% of Ouagadougou residents spoke French as their first language.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Linguists have observed the development of a local vernacular of French in the country called français populaire burkinabè which is influenced by local languages such as Mooré and is used as a lingua franca in commerce.
[src:auregnais/african-french] It is largely used as a spoken language whereas speakers continue to use standard French as the written language.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Cameroonian French is a variety of French spoken in Cameroon.
[src:auregnais/african-french] As a former French colony, the country's history has shaped its language, resulting in a distinct variant of French that reflects the country's diverse cultural, linguistic, and historical background.
[src:auregnais/african-french] With more than 11 million inhabitants, Kinshasa is the largest Francophone city in the world, surpassing Paris in population.
[src:auregnais/african-french] It is the capital of the most populous francophone country in the world, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, where an estimated 43 million people (51% of the total population) can speak French (essentially as a second language).
[src:auregnais/african-french] Contrary to Abidjan where French is the first language of a large part of the population, in Kinshasa French is only a second language, and its status of *lingua franca* is shared with Lingala.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Kinshasa French also differs from other African French variants, for it has some Belgian French influences, due to colonization.
[src:auregnais/african-french] People of different African mother tongues living in Kinshasa usually speak Lingala to communicate with each other in the street, but French is the language of businesses, administrations, schools, newspapers and televisions.
[src:auregnais/african-french] French is also the predominant written language.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Due to its widespread presence in Kinshasa, French has become a local language with its own pronunciation and some local words borrowed for the most part from Lingala.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Depending on their social status, some people may mix French and Lingala, or code switch between the two depending on the context.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Here are examples of words particular to Kinshasa French.
[src:auregnais/african-french] As in Abidjan, there exist various registers and the most educated people may frown upon the use of slangish/Lingala terms.
[src:auregnais/african-french] There are many linguistic differences that occur in Kinshasa French that make it a distinct dialect of French.
[src:auregnais/african-french] Similarly to many other African dialects of French, many of the linguistic aspects are influenced, either directly or indirectly, by the linguistics of the local African languages.
[src:auregnais/african-french] It is also essential to note that grammatical differences between local Congolese languages and the French language, such as the lack of gendered nouns in the former, result in linguistic changes when speakers of the former speak French.
[src:auregnais/african-french] As briefly mentioned above, many Congolese languages are ungendered languages and so there is often some mixing of the French masculine and feminine articles in speakers of Kinshasa French, such as the phrase *Je veux du banane* rather than the "correct" French *Je veux de la banane*.
[src:auregnais/alba] The term first appears in classical texts as Ἀλβίων **Albíōn** or Ἀλουΐων **Alouíōn** (in Ptolemy's writings in Greek), and later as **Albion** in Latin documents.
[src:auregnais/alba] Historically, the term refers to Britain as a whole and is ultimately based on the Indo-European root for "white".
[src:auregnais/alba] It later came to be used by Gaelic speakers in the form of **Alba** (dative **Albainn**, genitive **Albann**, now obsolete) as the name given to the former kingdom of the Picts which, when first used in this sense (around the time of king Causantín mac Áeda (Constantine II, 943–952)), had expanded.
[src:auregnais/alba] The region of Breadalbane (**Bràghad Albann**, the upper part of "Alba") takes its name from it as well.
[src:auregnais/alba] As time passed, that kingdom incorporated other territories to its south.
[src:auregnais/alba] It became re-Latinised in the High Medieval period as "Albania" (it is unclear whether it may ultimately share the same etymon as the modern Albania).
[src:auregnais/alba] This latter word was employed mainly by Celto-Latin writers, and most famously by Geoffrey of Monmouth.
[src:auregnais/alba] It was this word which passed into Middle English as Albany, although very rarely was this used for the Kingdom of Scotland, but rather for the notional Duchy of Albany.
[src:auregnais/alba] It is from the latter that Albany, the capital of the US state of New York, and Albany, Western Australia, take their names.
[src:auregnais/alba] BBC Alba, a television channel broadcasting mainly in Scottish Gaelic, was launched in September 2008 as a joint venture between the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) and Gaelic company MG Alba.
[src:auregnais/alba] A new version of Runrig's song *Alba* (originally on their album, *The Cutter and the Clan*) was featured on the channel's launch.
[src:auregnais/alba] In the mid-1990s, the Celtic League started a campaign to have the word "Alba" on the Scottish football and rugby tops.
[src:auregnais/alba] Since 2005, the SFA have supported the use of Scottish Gaelic by adding *Alba* on the back of the official team strip.
[src:auregnais/alba] However, as of 2008, the SRU is still being lobbied to have *Alba* added to the national rugby union strip.
[src:auregnais/alba] In 2007, the then Scottish Executive re-branded itself as "The Scottish Government" and started to use a bilingual logo with the Gaelic name *Riaghaltas na h-Alba*.
[src:auregnais/alba] However, the Gaelic version from the outset had always been *Riaghaltas na h-Alba*.
[src:auregnais/alba] The Scottish Parliament, likewise, uses the Gaelic name *Pàrlamaid na h-Alba*.
[src:auregnais/alba] A new welcome sign on the historic A7 route into Scotland was erected in 2009, with the text *Fàilte gu Alba*.
[src:auregnais/alba] Phrases such as *Alba gu bràth* may be used as a catch-phrase or rallying cry.
[src:auregnais/alba] It was used in the movie *Braveheart* as William Wallace encouraged the troops at the Battle of Stirling Bridge.
[src:auregnais/alba] In March 2021, former first minister of Scotland and leader of the SNP Alex Salmond launched the pro-independence Alba Party, set to contest the 2021 Scottish Parliament elections.
[src:auregnais/albion] The name for Scotland in most of the Celtic languages is related to Albion: *Alba* in Scottish Gaelic, *Albain* (genitive *Alban*) in Irish, *Nalbin* in Manx and *Alban* in Welsh and Cornish.
[src:auregnais/albion] These names were later Latinised as *Albania* and Anglicised as *Albany*, which were once alternative names for Scotland.
[src:auregnais/albion] The toponym in English is thought to derive from the Greek word Ἀλβίων mentioned by pseudo-Aristotle in *De Mundo*, Latinised as *Albiōn* (genitive *Albionis*).
[src:auregnais/albion] It is similarly mentioned by Ptolemy in his Geography and Pliny in the *Naturalis Historia*.
[src:auregnais/albion] The root **albiyo-* is also found in Gaulish and Galatian *albio-* 'world' and Welsh *elfydd* (Old Welsh *elbid* 'earth, world, land, country, district').
[src:auregnais/albion] It may be related to other European and Mediterranean toponyms such as *Alpes*, *Albania* or the river god Alpheus (originally 'whitish'). which has a possible etymology in the Proto-Indo-European word **albʰo-* 'white' (cf.
[src:auregnais/albion] The derivation from a word for 'white' is thought to refer perhaps to the white Cliffs of Dover in the southeast, visible from mainland Europe and a landmark at the narrowest crossing point.
[src:auregnais/albion] On the other hand, Celtic linguist Xavier Delamarre argued that it originally meant 'the world above, the visible world', in opposition to 'the world below', i.e. the underworld.
[src:auregnais/albion] 320 BC), as directly or indirectly quoted in the surviving excerpts of his works in later writers, speaks of *Albiōn and Iernē* (Great Britain and Ireland).
[src:auregnais/albion] Pytheas's grasp of the νῆσος Πρεττανική (*nēsos Prettanikē*, "Prettanic island") is somewhat blurry, and appears to include anything he considers a western island, including *Thule*.
[src:auregnais/albion] The name *Albion* was used by Isidore of Charax (1st century BC – 1st century AD) and subsequently by many classical writers.
[src:auregnais/albion] By the 1st century AD, the name refers unequivocally to Great Britain.
[src:auregnais/albion] But this "enigmatic name for Britain, revived much later by Romantic poets like William Blake, did not remain popular among Greek writers.
[src:auregnais/albion] It was soon replaced by Πρεττανία (*Prettanía*) and Βρεττανία (*Brettanía* 'Britain'), Βρεττανός (*Brettanós* 'Briton'), and Βρεττανικός (*Brettanikós*, meaning the adjective British).
[src:auregnais/albion] From these words the Romans derived the Latin forms Britannia, Britannus, and Britannicus respectively".
[src:auregnais/albion] ἐν τούτῳ γε μὴν νῆσοι μέγισται τυγχάνουσιν οὖσαι δύο, Βρεττανικαὶ λεγόμεναι, Ἀλβίων καὶ Ἰέρνη, τῶν προϊστορημένων μείζους, ὑπὲρ τοὺς Κελτοὺς κείμεναι.
[src:auregnais/albion] There are two very large islands in it, called the British Isles, Albion and Ierne; they are larger than those already mentioned, and lie beyond the land of the Celts.
[src:auregnais/albion] Pliny the Elder, in the fourth book of his *Natural History* (Latin: *Naturalis historia*) likewise calls Great Britain *Albion*.
[src:auregnais/albion] He begins his chapter on the British Isles (Latin: *Britanniae*, lit.
[src:auregnais/albion] Ex adverso huius situs Britannia insula clara Graecis nostrisque monimentis inter septentrionem et occidentem iacet, Germaniae, Galliae, Hispaniae, multo maximis Europae partibus magno intervallo adversa.
[src:auregnais/albion] Albion ipsi nomen fuit, cum Britanniae vocarentur omnes de quibus mox paulo dicemus.
[src:auregnais/albion] Opposite to this region lies the island of Britain, famous in the Greek records and in our own; it lies to the north-west, facing, across a wide channel, Germany, Gaul and Spain, countries which constitute by far the greater part of Europe.
[src:auregnais/albion] It was itself named Albion, while all the islands about which we shall soon briefly speak were called the Britains.
[src:auregnais/albion] In his 2nd century *Geography*, Ptolemy uses the name Ἀλουΐων (*Alouiōn*, "Albion") instead of the Roman name *Britannia*, possibly following the commentaries of Marinus of Tyre.
[src:auregnais/albion] He calls both Albion and Ierne in Ancient Greek: νῆσοι Βρεττανικαὶ, romanized: *nēsoi Brettanikai*, lit.
[src:auregnais/albion] In 930, the English king Æthelstan used the title *rex et primicerius totius Albionis regni*, 'king and chief of the whole realm of Albion'.
[src:auregnais/albion] His nephew, Edgar the Peaceful, styled himself in 970: *totius Albionis imperator augustus*, 'august emperor of all Albion'.
[src:auregnais/albion] A legend exists in various forms that giants were either the original inhabitants, or the founders of the land named Albion.
[src:auregnais/albion] After many adventures, Brutus and his fellow Trojans escape from Gaul and "set sail with a fair wind towards the promised island".
[src:auregnais/albion] "The island was then called Albion, and inhabited by none but a few giants.
[src:auregnais/albion] Geoffrey goes on to recount how the last of the giants are defeated, the largest one called Goëmagot is flung over a cliff by Corineus.
[src:auregnais/albion] The 13th century Prose *Merlin* drew on Geoffrey's story, but instead had Brutus and Corneus as two barons of Troy, who fled the city after its destruction.
[src:auregnais/albion] Brutus went to Britain and founded London, while Corneus, who was descended from giants, went to Britanny, where he founded cities and castles, and gave his name to Cornouaille.
[src:auregnais/albion] In this version the giants were descended from Corneus, and survived until the time of King Arthur, when they fought alongside the Saracens against the Britons during the Saxon invasion of Britain.
[src:auregnais/albion] Later, in the 14th century, a more elaborate tale was developed, claiming that Albina and her sisters founded Albion and procreated there a race of giants.
[src:auregnais/albion] The "Albina story" survives in several forms, including the octosyllabic Anglo-Norman poem "Des grantz geanz" dating to 1300–1334.
[src:auregnais/albion] According to the poem, in the 3970th year of the creation of the world, a king of Greece married his thirty daughters into royalty, but the haughty brides colluded to eliminate their husbands so they would be subservient to no one.
[src:auregnais/albion] The youngest would not be party to the crime and divulged the plot, so the other princesses were confined to an unsteerable rudderless ship and set adrift, and after three days reached an uninhabited land later to be known as "Britain".
[src:auregnais/albion] The eldest daughter Albina (*Albine*) was the first to step ashore and lay claim to the land, naming it after herself.
[src:auregnais/albion] At first, the women gathered acorns and fruits, but once they learned to hunt and obtain meat, it aroused their lecherous desires.
[src:auregnais/albion] As no other humans inhabited the land, they mated with evil spirits called "incubi", and subsequently with the sons they begot, engendering a race of giants.
[src:auregnais/albion] These giants are evidenced by huge bones which are unearthed.
[src:auregnais/albion] Brutus arrived 260 years after Albina, 1136 before the birth of Christ, but by then there were only 24 giants left, due to inner strife.
[src:auregnais/albion] As with Geoffrey of Monmouth's version, Brutus's band subsequently overtake the land, defeating Gogmagog in the process.
[src:auregnais/albion] The octosyllabic poem appears as a prologue to 16 out of 26 manuscripts of the Short Version of the Anglo-Norman prose *Brut*, which derives from Wace.
[src:auregnais/albion] Octosyllabic is not the only form the Anglo-Norman *Des Grantz Geanz*, there are five forms, the others being: the alexandrine, prose, short verse, and short prose versions.
[src:auregnais/albion] The Latin adaptation of the Albina story, *De Origine Gigantum*, appeared soon afterwards, in the 1330s.
[src:auregnais/albion] It has been edited by Carey & Crick (1995), and translated by Ruth Evans (1998).
[src:auregnais/albion] A variant tale occurs in the Middle English prose *Brut* (Brie ed., *The Brut or the Chronicles of England* 1906–1908) of the 14th century, an English rendition of the Anglo-Norman *Brut* deriving from Wace.
[src:auregnais/albion] In the Prolog of this chronicle, it was King "Dioclician" of "Surrey" (Syria), who had 33 daughters, the eldest being called "Albyne".
[src:auregnais/albion] The princesses are all banished to Albion after plotting to murder their husbands, where they couple with the local demons; their offspring became a race of giants.
[src:auregnais/albion] The chronicle asserts that during the voyage Albyne entrusted the fate of the sisters to "Appolyn", which was the god of their faith.
[src:auregnais/albion] The Syrian king who was her father sounds much like a Roman emperor, though Diocletian (3rd century) would be anachronistic, and Holinshed explains this as a bungling of the legend of Danaus and his fifty daughters who founded Argos.
[src:auregnais/albion] Because Geoffrey of Monmouth's work was regarded as fact until the late 17th century, the story appears in most early histories of Britain.
[src:auregnais/albion] Wace, Layamon, Raphael Holinshed, William Camden and John Milton repeat the legend and it appears in Edmund Spenser's *The Faerie Queene*.
[src:auregnais/albion] William Blake's poems *Milton* and *Jerusalem* feature Albion as an archetypal giant representing humanity.
[src:auregnais/albion] In 2010, artist Mark Sheeky donated the 2008 painting *Two Roman Legionaries Discovering The God-King Albion Turned Into Stone* to the Grosvenor Museum collection.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney has an area of 3 square miles (8 km2), making it the third-largest island of the Channel Islands, and the second-largest in the bailiwick only to the island of Guernsey itself.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney is around 10 miles (16 km) to the west of the Cap de la Hague on the Cotentin Peninsula, Normandy, in France, 20 miles (32 km) to the northeast of Guernsey and 60 miles (100 km) from the south coast of Great Britain.
[src:auregnais/alderney] It is the closest of the Channel Islands both to France and to the United Kingdom.
[src:auregnais/alderney] It is separated from the Cap de la Hague by the dangerous Alderney Race (French: *Raz Blanchard*).
[src:auregnais/alderney] As of March 2023, the island had a population of 2,167; natives are traditionally nicknamed *vaques* after the cows, or else *lapins* after the many rabbits seen in the island.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Formally, they are known as *Ridunians*, from the Latin *Riduna*.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The only parish of Alderney is the parish of St Anne, which covers the whole island.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The main town, Saint Anne, historically known as *La Ville* ('The Town'), is often referred to as *St Anne's* by visitors and incomers, but rarely by locals (who, in normal conversation, still most frequently refer to the area centred on Victoria Street simply as *Town*).
[src:auregnais/alderney] The town's "High Street", which formerly had a small handful of shops, is now almost entirely residential, forming a T-junction with Victoria Street at its highest point.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The town area features an imposing church and an unevenly cobbled main street: Victoria Street (*Rue Grosnez*, the English name being adopted on the visit of Queen Victoria in 1854).
[src:auregnais/alderney] There is one school (providing both primary and secondary education), a post office, hotels, restaurants, shops, and a bank.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Other settlements include: Braye, Crabby, Longis, Mannez, La Banque, and Newtown.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney shares its prehistory with the other islands in the Bailiwick of Guernsey; it became an island in the Neolithic period as the waters of the English Channel rose.
[src:auregnais/alderney] A cist survives near Fort Tourgis, and Longis Common has remains of an Iron Age site.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The etymology of the island's name is obscure.
[src:auregnais/alderney] It is known in Latin as *Riduna* but, as with the names of all the Channel Islands in the Roman period, there is a degree of confusion.
[src:auregnais/alderney] *Riduna* may be the original name of Tatihou, while Alderney is conjectured to be identified with *Sarnia*.
[src:auregnais/alderney] *Alderney*/*Aurigny* is variously supposed to be a Germanic or Celtic name.
[src:auregnais/alderney] It may be a corruption of *Adreni* or *Alrene*, which is probably derived from an Old Norse word meaning "island near the coast".
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alternatively, it may derive from three Norse elements: *alda* (swelling wave, roller), *renna* (strong current, race) and *öy* or *-ey* (island).
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney may be mentioned in Paul the Deacon's *Historia Langobardorum* (I.6) as 'Evodia' in which he discussed a certain dangerous whirlpool.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The name 'Evodia' may in turn originate from the seven 'Haemodae' of uncertain identification in Pliny the Elder's *Natural History* (IV 16 (30) or Pomponius Mela's *Chronographia* (III 6,54).
[src:auregnais/alderney] Along with the other Channel Islands, Alderney was annexed by the Duchy of Normandy in 933.
[src:auregnais/alderney] In 1042, William the Bastard, Duke of Normandy (later William the Conqueror, King of the English), granted Alderney to the Abbey of Mont Saint-Michel.
[src:auregnais/alderney] In 1057, the Bishop of Coutances took back control of the island.
[src:auregnais/alderney] After 1204, when mainland Normandy was incorporated into the Kingdom of France, Alderney remained loyal to the English monarch in his dignity of Duke of Normandy.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Henry VIII of England undertook fortification works, but these ceased in 1554.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Essex Castle perpetuates the name of the Earl of Essex, who purchased the governorship of Alderney in 1591.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Prior to the Earl's execution for treason in 1601, he leased the island to William Chamberlain, and Alderney remained in the hands of the Chamberlain family until 1643.
[src:auregnais/alderney] From 1612, a Judge was appointed to assist the Governor's administration of Alderney, along with the Jurats.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The function of the Judge was similar to that of the Bailiffs of Guernsey and Jersey, and continued until 1949.
[src:auregnais/alderney] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms, Alderney was held by a Parliamentary garrison under Nicholas Ling, Lieutenant-Governor.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Ling built Government House (now the Island Hall).
[src:auregnais/alderney] The de Carterets of Jersey acquired the governorship, later passing it to Sir Edmund Andros of Guernsey, from whom the Guernsey family of Le Mesurier inherited it, thus establishing a hereditary line of governors that lasted until 1825.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Henry Le Mesurier prospered through privateering, and moved the harbour from Longis to Braye, building a jetty there in 1736.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Warehouses and dwellings were built at Braye, and the export of cattle generated wealth for the economy.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Court House was built in 1770 and a school in 1790.
[src:auregnais/alderney] A Methodist chapel was constructed in 1790, following John Wesley's visit in 1787.
[src:auregnais/alderney] An optical telegraph tower was constructed above La Foulère in 1811, enabling signals to be relayed visually to Le Mât in Sark and on to Guernsey – early warning of attack during the Napoleonic Wars was of strategic importance.
[src:auregnais/alderney] With the end of those wars privateering was ended and smuggling suppressed, leading to economic difficulties.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The last of the hereditary Governors, John Le Mesurier, resigned his patent to the Crown in 1825, and since then authority has been exercised by the States of Alderney, as amended by the constitutional settlement of 1948.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The British Government decided to undertake massive fortifications in the 19th century and to create a strategic harbour to deter attacks from France.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The harbour was never completed – the remaining breakwater (designed by James Walker) is one of the island's landmarks, and is longer than any breakwater in the UK.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Queen Victoria and Prince Albert visited Alderney on 9 August 1854.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Albert Memorial and the renaming of Rue Grosnez to Victoria Street commemorate this visit.
[src:auregnais/alderney] At the same time as the breakwater was being built in the 1850s, the island was fortified by a string of 13 forts, designed to protect the harbour of refuge.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The accommodation quarters of several of the forts have been converted into apartments; two are now private homes; and one, Fort Clonque, at the end of a causeway that can be flooded at high tide, belongs to the Landmark Trust and can be rented for holidays.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Scenes from the film *Seagulls Over Sorrento* were shot at Fort Clonque in 1953.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Some of the forts are now in varying stages of dereliction, the most ruined being Les Hommeaux Florains, perched on outlying rocks, its access causeway and bridge having been swept away long ago.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Houmet Herbé resembles a Crusader castle with its squat round towers.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Like many of the forts, it included such apparently anachronistic features as a drawbridge and machicolation, which were still common in military architecture of the period.
[src:auregnais/alderney] In June 1940, almost the entire population of Alderney of 1,400 was evacuated to Britain.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Most went on the official evacuation boats sent from mainland Britain.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Some, however, decided to make their own way, mostly via Guernsey, but due to the impending occupation many found themselves unable to leave and were forced to stay on Guernsey for the duration of the war.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Eighteen Alderney people elected not to leave with the general evacuation.
[src:auregnais/alderney] However, boats from Guernsey came and collected some of them before the German Army arrived, on the basis that it was best for their personal safety.
[src:auregnais/alderney] During the Second World War, the Channel Islands were the only part of the British Isles that was occupied by Germany, although other parts of the Empire were occupied by the Axis powers.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Germans arrived to a nearly deserted island, and began to follow their orders to fortify Alderney as part of Hitler's Atlantic Wall.
[src:auregnais/alderney] In January 1942, they built four camps in Alderney: two work camps, Lager Helgoland and Lager Borkum, and two concentration camps, Lager Sylt and Lager Norderney.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The jail behind the main police station was used by the Nazis as a prison.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The camps were built by the Nazi Organisation Todt (OT) to house the labour used to build fortifications including bunkers, gun emplacements, tunnels, air-raid shelters and other concrete and field fortifications.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Lager Norderney, containing Russian and Polish POWs, and the Lager Sylt camp holding Jewish slave labourers, were transferred to SS administration in March 1943 under the control of *Hauptsturmführer* Maximilian List.
[src:auregnais/alderney] There are 397 graves in Alderney, which when added to the men who died in ships, takes the total to over 700 out of a total inmate population of 6,000 who died before the camps were closed and the remaining inmates transferred to France in 1944.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Evidence, however, was all over the island, with concrete fortifications and graveyards for the prisoners kept there during the occupation.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Royal Navy blockaded the islands from time to time, particularly following the liberation of Normandy in 1944.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Intense negotiations resulted in some Red Cross humanitarian aid, but there was considerable hunger and privation during the five years of German occupation, particularly in the final months when the Germans themselves were close to starvation.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Germans surrendered Alderney on 16 May 1945, eight days after the Allies formally accepted the unconditional surrender of the armed forces of Nazi Germany and the end of World War II in Europe, and seven days after the liberation of Guernsey and Jersey.
[src:auregnais/alderney] 2,332 German prisoners of war were removed from Alderney on 20 May 1945, leaving 500 Germans to undertake clearing up operations under British military supervision.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The people of Alderney could not start returning until December 1945 due to the huge cleanup operation needed simply to make the island safe for civilians.
[src:auregnais/alderney] When the islanders returned home they were shocked to see the state of the island, with many houses completely derelict: the Germans had burned anything wooden, including front doors, for fuel.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Archival and object evidence of the general evacuation in 1940 and the subsequent occupation of Alderney can be found in the Alderney Society Museum.
[src:auregnais/alderney] In 1949, two former SS officials from the Lager Norderney concentration camp, SS Obersturmführer Adam Adler and Lagerführer Heinrich Evers, were prosecuted in France for crimes committed during their administration of the camp.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Adler was sentenced to ten years, while Evers received a seven-year sentence.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Members of the Association des Anciens Déportés d'Aurigny considered the sentences overly lenient.
[src:auregnais/alderney] A 1945 British military report, known as the Pantcheff Report, documented that eight French nationals had perished in the Alderney camps.
[src:auregnais/alderney] In May 2024, an investigative commission led by Lord Pickles concluded that between 641 and 1,027 individuals likely died in the Nazi camps on Alderney.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The report highlighted the atrocious conditions faced by forced labourers, who endured starvation, dangerously long hours, hazardous construction tasks, frequent abuse, torture, inadequate housing, and, in some cases, execution.
[src:auregnais/alderney] A series of tunnels also remain in place on Alderney, constructed by forced labour.
[src:auregnais/alderney] These are in varying degrees of decay, being left open to the public and the elements.
[src:auregnais/alderney] For two years after the end of the war, Alderney was operated as a communal farm.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Craftsmen were paid by their employers, while others were paid by the local government out of the profit from the sales of farm produce.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Remaining profits were put aside to repay the British Government for repairing and rebuilding the island.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The local people resented being unable to control their own land; this led to the United Kingdom Home Office setting up an enquiry that led to the "Government of Alderney Law 1948", which came into force on 1 January 1949.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The law organised the construction and election of the States of Alderney and the justice system; and, for the first time in Alderney, the imposition of taxes.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The legislature and judiciary were separated.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The position of Judge, who had headed the island's government since the resignation of the last Governor in 1825, was abolished, and the Jurats were removed from their legislative function.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Because of the island's small population, it was believed that the island could not be self-sufficient in running the airport and the harbour, or providing services that would match those of the UK.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Taxes were therefore collected into the general Bailiwick of Guernsey revenue funds at the same rate as in Guernsey, and administered by the States of Guernsey.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Guernsey became responsible for providing many government functions and services.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The 20th century saw much change in Alderney, from the building of the airport in the late 1930s to the death of the last speakers of the island's Auregnais language, a dialect of the Norman language.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The economy has gone from depending largely on agriculture to earning money from the tourism and finance industries.
[src:auregnais/alderney] E-commerce has become increasingly important, and the island hosts the domain name registry for both Bailiwicks and dozens of gambling website operators.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney has a full regulatory authority in operation.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The States of Alderney (French: États d'Aurigny) is the legislature of the island; it sends two representatives to the States of Guernsey as well.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The origin of the States is unknown, but it has operated from the Middle Ages.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The States of Alderney consists of the President, directly elected every four years, and ten States Members, half elected every two years for a four-year mandate.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The whole island is a single constituency.
[src:auregnais/alderney] William Tate was elected president in June 2019.
[src:auregnais/alderney] These are known as 'the transferred services'.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Transferred services include policing, customs and excise, airport operations, health, education, social services, childcare and adoption.
[src:auregnais/alderney] (The States of Alderney retains policy control of aviation to and from the island).
[src:auregnais/alderney] In return for providing the transferred services Guernsey levies various taxes and duties on Alderney.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Immigration is the responsibility of the UK (UK law applies), with day-to-day operations carried out by the Guernsey Border Agency.
[src:auregnais/alderney] In addition to the transferred services, both the UK and Guernsey may legislate on other matters with the consent of the States of Alderney.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Court of Alderney exercises unlimited original jurisdiction in civil matters and limited jurisdiction in criminal matters.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Court sits with a Chairman (the Judge of Alderney) and at least three of the six Jurats.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Appeals are made to the Royal Court of Guernsey, which also exercises some original jurisdiction in criminal matters in Alderney, and thence to the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council.
[src:auregnais/alderney] For a number of taxation purposes, Alderney is treated as if it were part of Guernsey.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Income Tax is administered by the Guernsey Revenue Service but there are some differences between Alderney and Guernsey Income Tax, specifically in the matter of the cap on Income Tax (which is set lower in Alderney than in Guernsey).
[src:auregnais/alderney] From 2016, Alderney took back control of Tax on Real Property (TRP).
[src:auregnais/alderney] From 2021, Alderney is responsible for setting the rate and collecting the Taxation on Real Property (TRP), with Occupier's Rates (OR) now included within that bill.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney now also receives Motor Fuel Excise Duty and Document Duty on property conveyances.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The climate of Alderney is temperate, moderated by the sea, and summers are usually warmer than elsewhere in the British Isles.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Under the Köppen climate classification, Alderney has an oceanic climate (Cfb), similar to a warm-summer Mediterranean climate (Csb).
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney has cool, wet winters and mild summers with moderate rainfall.
[src:auregnais/alderney] February is the coldest month with an average high of 8 °C (47 °F), and a low of 4 °C (40 °F).
[src:auregnais/alderney] July and August are the warmest months, with an average high of 19 °C (66 °F), and a low of 13 to 14 °C (around 56 °F).
[src:auregnais/alderney] October is the wettest month with 107.2 mm (4.22 in) of rain, and April is the driest month with 42.4 mm (1.67 in).
[src:auregnais/alderney] Average annual sunshine hours are around 1780.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney is similar to the other Channel Islands in having sheer cliffs broken by stretches of sandy beach and dunes.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The highest point is on the central plateau of the island at 296 feet (90 metres).
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney and its surrounding islets support a rich flora and fauna.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Trees are rather scarce, as many were cut down in the 17th century to fuel the lighthouses on Alderney and the Casquets.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Those trees that remain include cabbage trees (due to the mild climate – often miscalled "palms" but of the asparagus family), and there are some small woods dotted about the island.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Puffins on Burhou and gannet on Les Étacs (popularly called Gannet Rock) just off Alderney are a favourite of many visitors to the island.
[src:auregnais/alderney] About a quarter of Alderney hedgehogs are of the "white" or "blonde" variety, which does not carry fleas.
[src:auregnais/alderney] These are not albinos, but descent of rarely met blonde European hedgehogs, with a blonde pair released on the island in the 1960s.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The island had its own breed of cattle, called the Alderney.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The pure breed became extinct in 1944, but hybrids remain elsewhere, though no longer on Alderney.
[src:auregnais/alderney] In August 2005, the west coast of Alderney and associated islands, including Burhou and Ortac, were designated as Ramsar wetlands of international importance.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Alderney Wildlife Trust helps to manage the two nature reserves, at Longis and Vau du Saou.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The island is surrounded by rocks, which have caused hundreds of wrecks.
[src:auregnais/alderney] There are treacherous tidal streams on either side of the island: the Swinge between Alderney and Burhou, just outside the harbour, and Le Raz between the island and the Normandy mainland.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The geology of Alderney is mostly granites from the Precambrian period.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The language of the island is now English with a few minor variants, comprising a form of Channel Island English.
[src:auregnais/alderney] For centuries the island had its own dialect of the Norman language called Auregnais, now extinct.
[src:auregnais/alderney] It was primarily a spoken language, with only a few known poems and written works using it.
[src:auregnais/alderney] French was once widely used on the island, and increasingly replaced Auregnais from the late 19th century onward, but it ceased to be an official language there in 1966.
[src:auregnais/alderney] However, there is a strong cultural legacy of both languages in the island: most of the local place-names are in French or Auregnais, as are many local surnames.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The pronunciation of various local names is also dialectal, e.g.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Dupont as "dip-oh" rather than in the traditional Parisian fashion, and Saye (the name of a beach on the island) as "soy".
[src:auregnais/alderney] One or two French/Auregnais words are still in common use, e.g.
[src:auregnais/alderney] *vraic* (seaweed fertiliser), as well as *impôt,* which is the word used for the island's landfill.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Island sports include golf, fishing and water sports, supported by clubs and associations.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney competes in the biennial Island Games.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Athletes from Alderney have also competed at the Commonwealth Games as part of the Guernsey team.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Every September, the Alderney Air Races attract a number of aircraft to compete in the deciding and final round for the European Air Racing championship, organised by the Royal Aero Club.
[src:auregnais/alderney] This involves high-speed circuits round the airfield, lighthouse, Casquets and then back around.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Alderney football team plays in the annual Muratti Vase alongside teams from fellow Channel Islands, Guernsey and Jersey.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Since the competition started in 1905, Alderney's sole championship victory was in 1920.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Partly because of the tourist industry, but mainly to the Ridunians' own drinking culture (there is a common expression elsewhere in the Channel Islands that Alderney is composed of 'two thousand alcoholics, clinging to a rock'), there are many restaurants and public houses.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The States of Alderney passed pub anti-smoking legislation recently in comparison to the rest of the British Isles.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Following the President's casting vote on 13 January 2010, the legislation came into force at 4 am on 1 June 2010 with Guernsey, Jersey, the UK, and the Isle of Man all having outlawed this at a previous stage.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Notable residents of Alderney include authors T.
[src:auregnais/alderney] White (*The Once and Future King*) and Elisabeth Beresford (The Wombles), cricket commentator John Arlott, cricketer Sir Ian Botham, Beatles producer Sir George Martin, actress Dame Julie Andrews, and Olympic swimmer Duncan Goodhew.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Local TV coverage is provided by BBC Channel Islands and ITV Channel Television.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Television signals are received from the island's relay transmitter situated in the eastern part of Alderney.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The island is also served by both BBC Radio Guernsey on 99 FM and Island FM on 93.7 FM which both broadcast from St.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney has its own radio station, QUAY-FM, which broadcasts on 107.1 and online.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Initially it only operated at seasonal highpoints such as the summer Alderney Week festival, but from 2015 it has broadcast 24 hours a day.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney Week is the island's annual summer festival, beginning the first Monday of August and lasting six days, it involves islanders and attracts visitors.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Miss Alderney is chosen during the Easter Holiday weekend each year at a public event held at the Island Hall.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Comedy Rocks is an annual run of live stand up comedy gigs mid to late July and early August.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The shows feature well known and established comedians from the UK comedy circuit, and have so far featured BBC Radio 4's Marcus Brigstocke, Zoe Lyons and *I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here!* runner-up Joel Dommett.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Every year in mid-September Alderney hosts a motorsport weekend that is organized by the Guernsey Kart and Motor Club.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The event has been held for more than 20 years.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The event attracts Guernsey drivers who come to Alderney with high powered cars, motorbikes, sidecars and karts.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Race vehicles are shipped to Alderney two days before the event.
[src:auregnais/alderney] On the Friday, a sprint is held on the public roads of Fort Corbelets in the east of the island which are closed for the event.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The following day a hill climb is held at Fort Tourgis in the west of the island and on a public road which is closed for the event.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Local Alderney people watch as the closed roads have vehicles racing at high speed where normally speed limits of 35 miles per hour (56 kilometres per hour) apply.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The annual Alderney Performing Arts Festival began in 2013, and features music, dance and theatre.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Alderney Literary Festival began in March 2015, with talks and events relating to historical fiction and non-fiction.
[src:auregnais/alderney] It is organised by the Alderney Literary Trust.
[src:auregnais/alderney] In April 2011, sculptor Andy Goldsworthy completed a project called Alderney Stones, commenced in 2008, in which 11 large dried-earth spheres were placed at different sites on the island.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The intention is that each stone will gradually erode, at different speeds depending on the location, and in some cases revealing objects buried inside.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Materials included clay, earth, chain, old work gloves, bricks, hawser, wheat, wire, blackberries, poppy seeds and tools.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Previously there was a school called Ormer House Preparatory School which closed in December 2013.
[src:auregnais/alderney] There are several flights each day from Southampton and Guernsey, with links to many parts of the United Kingdom and Europe.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Aurigny serves the island with Dornier 228s.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Boats sail regularly between the island and France, and to the other Channel Islands.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Manche Iles Express operates a high-speed passenger ferry in summer to Diélette in the commune of Flamanville, Manche in France, and to St Peter Port, Guernsey.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Two boats offer seasonal service to Guernsey.
[src:auregnais/alderney] A 12-passenger boat operates services to Cherbourg Harbour, Sark and St Peter Port.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney is 72.5 miles (116.7 kilometres) from St Malo and 70.3 miles (113.1 kilometres) from Poole.
[src:auregnais/alderney] There are boat trips, water-taxi services and water and fuel access to visiting yacht crews.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The busiest time is during the peak months of June, July and August as nearly 30,000 yacht crew members visit this harbour every year.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Because of the island's size, vehicular transport is often unnecessary, although taxis, cars and bicycles are used.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Alderney Railway is the only remaining railway in the Channel Islands; it gives a timetabled public service, with scheduled trains to the lighthouse during the summer and special occasions such as Easter and Christmas.
[src:auregnais/alderney] There is an occasional bus service around the island.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Alderney allows people to ride motorbikes and mopeds without helmets and drive cars without seatbelts, but it is compulsory for those under 18 to wear helmets.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The international vehicle registration code is *GBA*.
[src:auregnais/alderney] As in the rest of the Bailiwick of Guernsey, mopeds and motorbikes with an engine of 50cc or less can be driven from the age of 14 with a provisional licence.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Alderney Water Board is responsible for the supply of water on the island.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Water is sourced from bore holes and streams and is treated and stored at Corblets Quarry and Battery Quarry.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Electricity was first supplied on Alderney in 1934 by Mr.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The supply concession was transferred to Alderney Light and Power Company in 1939, which came under the control of the States of Guernsey Electricity Department, before reverting to the States of Alderney in 1950.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Supplies from a new power station operated by Alderney Electricity Limited started on 1 April 1952.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Electricity is generated by fuel oil driven generators.
[src:auregnais/alderney] There are 3 × 2,000 kW, 2 × 50 kW and 2 × 450 kW engine generators.
[src:auregnais/alderney] As of 2020, there are currently plans to develop tidal power and to construct a 220 kilometre France-Alderney-Britain cable link.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Alderney Voluntary Fire Brigade has a crew of 12 volunteer firefighters, and operates one Iveco Daily light water tender with a 10.5 m ladder, two Iveco water carriers each with a capacity of 4,500 litres, one Ford Ranger rapid response unit and two trailer units.
[src:auregnais/alderney] A new fire station was officially opened on 20 October 2004 by Lt.-General Sir John Foley, the Lieutenant Governor of Guernsey.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The fire station is near Braye Harbour, has four appliance bays, a workshop, kit room, mess and a training room, and achieves an average response time of nine minutes.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Alderney Airport Fire and Rescue Service is sometimes called on to help with larger conflagrations.
[src:auregnais/alderney] In 2020, the Ambulance service merged into the Fire service to form the first combined fire and ambulance service in the British Isles outside of Dublin.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Until 2020, the St John Alderney Ambulance Service operated the ambulance service on the island, and was staffed by volunteers.
[src:auregnais/alderney] It had served Alderney since 1952 and was registered as a private company.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Patients are transferred to the Mignot Memorial Hospital in St Anne, and any having major complications are then transferred to Guernsey or Southampton by the Aurigny between 7 am and 7 pm on an emergency basis.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Outside these hours or in the event of bad weather preventing an air evacuation the transfer is achieved with the aid of the RNLI lifeboat service.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Because of Alderney's low crime rate, day-to-day policing of Alderney is provided by a team of five locally based officers from the Guernsey Police, consisting of a sergeant in charge, two constables, and two special constables.
[src:auregnais/alderney] They are regularly assisted by visiting constables from Guernsey.
[src:auregnais/alderney] The Alderney lifeboat station was established in 1869, was closed in 1884, and was re-established in 1985 by the RNLI.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Search and rescue services are provided by Channel Islands Air Search, which uses a Britten-Norman Islander to search large areas of water using infrared cameras and a number of other technologies.
[src:auregnais/alderney] Formed in 1980, it is staffed entirely by volunteers and is based in Guernsey.
[src:auregnais/alderney] When a major search is underway, the French coastguard and the Royal Navy are often involved, co-ordinated by the Maritime Rescue Co-ordination Centre in Jobourg, France.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] In his poetry, Swinburne rebelled against the Christian morality of the Victorian era, drawing from classical, medieval, and Renaissance sources to explore atheism in "Hymn to Proserpine", suicide in "The Triumph of Time", lesbian desire in "Anactoria", and sado-masochism in "Dolores".
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] While Swinburne's work attracted scandal, it had prominent Victorian defenders, including John Ruskin.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne's poetic style is rhythmic, alliterative, and sensual, and drew both critical acclaim and moral condemnation in his lifetime.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] His poems are often complex, working double rhymes and anapaestic metre into intricate stanzas.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne's style was shaped by that of the French poet Charles Baudelaire, author of the notorious Les Fleurs du mal, for whom Swinburne wrote the poetic eulogy "Ave Atque Vale".
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne was nominated for the Nobel Prize in Literature every year from 1903 to 1909.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] After the death of Alfred, Lord Tennyson in 1892, Swinburne was considered for the post of Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom, but was disqualified by Queen Victoria on moral grounds.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] His writings influenced Aesthetic and Decadent poets of the fin de siècle, such as Oscar Wilde and Ernest Dowson.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne was born at 7 Chester Street, Grosvenor Place, London, on 5 April 1837.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] He was the eldest of six children born to Captain (later Admiral) Charles Henry Swinburne (1797–1877) and Lady Jane Henrietta, daughter of the 3rd Earl of Ashburnham, a wealthy Northumbrian family.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] He grew up at East Dene in Bonchurch on the Isle of Wight.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] The Swinburnes also had a London home at Whitehall Gardens, Westminster.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] As a child, Swinburne was "nervous" and "frail", but "was also fired with nervous energy and fearlessness to the point of being reckless".
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] He rode horses and wrote plays with his first cousin Mary Gordon who lived nearby on the Isle of Wight.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] They secretly collaborated on her second book, *Children of the Chapel*, which contained an unusual number of beatings.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne attended Eton College (1849–53), where he began to write poetry.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] At Eton, he won first prizes in French and Italian.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] He attended Balliol College, Oxford (1856–60), with a brief hiatus when he was rusticated from the university in 1859 for publicly supporting the attempted assassination of Napoleon III by Felice Orsini.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] He returned in May 1860, but never received a degree.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] At Oxford, Swinburne met several Pre-Raphaelites, including Dante Gabriel Rossetti.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] After leaving college, he lived in London and started an active writing career, where Rossetti was delighted with his "little Northumbrian friend", probably a reference to Swinburne's diminutive height—he was just 5'4".
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne spent summer holidays at Capheaton Hall in Northumberland, the house of his grandfather, Sir John Swinburne, 6th Baronet (1762–1860), who had a famous library and was president of the Literary and Philosophical Society in Newcastle upon Tyne.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne considered Northumberland to be his native county, an emotion reflected in poems like the intensely patriotic "Northumberland", "Grace Darling" and others.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] He enjoyed riding his pony across the moors; he was a daring horseman, "through honeyed leagues of the northland border", as he called the Scottish border in his *Recollections*.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] In the period 1857–60, Swinburne became a member of Lady Trevelyan's intellectual circle at Wallington Hall.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] After his grandfather's death in 1860, Swinburne stayed with William Bell Scott in Newcastle.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] In 1861, Swinburne visited Menton on the French Riviera, staying at the Villa Laurenti to recover from the excessive use of alcohol.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] From Menton, Swinburne went to Italy, where he travelled extensively.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] In December 1862, Swinburne accompanied Scott and his guests, probably including Dante Gabriel Rossetti, on a trip to Tynemouth.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Despite the call of the sea, in October of 1868, Algernon Swinburne's life was spared by another young poet, Guy de Maupassant.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] At age 18, Maupassant saved him from drowning off the coast of Étretat.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne was an alcoholic and algolagniac and highly excitable.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] His health suffered, and in 1879 at the age of 42, he was taken into care by his friend, Theodore Watts-Dunton, who looked after him for the rest of his life at The Pines, 11 Putney Hill, Putney.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Watts-Dunton took him to the lost town of Dunwich, on the Suffolk coast, on several occasions in the 1870s.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] In Watts-Dunton's care Swinburne lost his youthful rebelliousness and developed into a figure of social respectability.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] It was said of Watts-Dunton that he saved the man and killed the poet.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne died at the Pines on 10 April 1909, at the age of 72, and was buried at St.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Boniface Church, Bonchurch on the Isle of Wight.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne's poetic works include *Atalanta in Calydon* (1865); *Poems and Ballads* (1866); *Songs before Sunrise* (1871); *Poems and Ballads Second Series* (1878); *Tristram of Lyonesse* (1882); *Poems and Ballads Third Series* (1889); and the novel *Lesbia Brandon* (published posthumously in 1952).
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] He was influenced by the work of William Shakespeare, Percy Bysshe Shelley, Catullus, William Morris, Dante Gabriel Rossetti, Robert Browning, Alfred Lord Tennyson, and Victor Hugo.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne was popular in England during his lifetime but his stature has greatly decreased since his death.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne devised the poetic form called the roundel, a variation of the French Rondeau, and examples of this form were included in *A Century of Roundels* dedicated to Christina Rossetti.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne wrote to Edward Burne-Jones in 1883: "I have got a tiny new book of songs or songlets, in one form and all manner of metres ... just coming out, of which Miss Rossetti has accepted the dedication.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] I hope you and Georgie [*his wife Georgiana, one of the MacDonald sisters*] will find something to like among a hundred poems of nine lines each, twenty-four of which are about babies or small children".
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Opinions about these poems vary, some finding them captivating and brilliant while others see them as over-clever and contrived.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] One of these poems, *A Baby's Death*, was set to music by the English composer Sir Edward Elgar as the song "Roundel: The little eyes that never knew Light".
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] English composer Mary Augusta Wakefield set Swinburne's *May Time in Midwinter* to music.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] After the first *Poems and Ballads*, Swinburne's later poetry became increasingly devoted to celebrations of republicanism and revolutionary causes, particularly in the volume *Songs before Sunrise*.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] "A Song of Italy" is dedicated to Giuseppe Mazzini; "Ode on the Proclamation of the French Republic" is dedicated to Victor Hugo; and "Dirae" is a sonnet sequence of vituperative attacks against those whom Swinburne believed to be enemies of liberty.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] *Erechtheus* is the culmination of Swinburne's republican verse.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] He did not stop writing love poetry entirely; indeed his epic-length poem *Tristram of Lyonesse* was produced during this period but its content is much less shocking than that of his earlier love poetry.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] His versification, and especially his rhyming technique, remained in top form to the end.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Renée Vivien, the English poet, was highly impressed with Swinburne and often included quotations from him in her works.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] In France, Swinburne was highly praised by the Symbolist poet Stéphane Mallarmé, and was invited to contribute to a book in honour of the poet Théophile Gautier, *Le tombeau de Théophile Gautier* (Wikisource): he answered by writing down six poems in French, English, Latin, and Greek.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] In the United States, horror fiction writer H.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Lovecraft considered Swinburne "the only real poet in either England or America after the death of Mr.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Swinburne is considered a poet of the Decadent school.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Rumours about his perversions often filled the broadsheets, and he ironically used to play along, confessing to being a pederast and having sex with monkeys.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Eliot read Swinburne's essays on the Shakespearean and Jonsonian dramatists in *The Contemporaries of Shakespeare* and *The Age of Shakespeare* and Swinburne's books on Shakespeare and Jonson.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Writing on Swinburne in *The Sacred Wood: Essays on Poetry and Criticism*, Eliot wrote Swinburne had mastered his material, and "he is a more reliable guide to [these dramatists] than Hazlitt, Coleridge, or Lamb: and his perception of relative values is almost always correct".
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Eliot wrote that Swinburne, as a poet, "mastered his technique, which is a great deal, but he did not master it to the extent of being able to take liberties with it, which is everything".
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Furthermore, Eliot disliked Swinburne's prose, about which he wrote "the tumultuous outcry of adjectives, the headstrong rush of undisciplined sentences, are the index to the impatience and perhaps laziness of a disorderly mind".
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] In 1908 he was one of the main candidates considered for the prize, and was nominated again in 1909.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Selections from his poems were translated into French by Gabriel Mourey: *Poèmes et ballades d'Algernon Charles Swinburne* (Paris, Albert Savine, 1891), incorporating notes by Guy de Maupassant; and *Chants d'avant l'aube de Swinburne* (Paris, P.-V.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] Italian Decadent writer Gabriele D'Annunzio repeatedly emulated Swinburne in his own poetry, and it is believed that his acquaintance with Swinburne was primarily through Mourey's French translations.
[src:auregnais/algernon-charles-swinburne] are traditionally included with "poetry".
[src:auregnais/auregnais] The dialect became extinct in the 20th century.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] Only a few examples of Auregnais survived, mostly in place names in Alderney, and one audio recording is known to exist.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] The last known native speaker of Auregnais died around 1960.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] Linguist Frank Le Maistre, author of the *Dictionnaire Jersiais-Français*, recorded the only known audio samples of the language, which he published in 1982.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] It is likely that the last rememberer died in the early 2020s.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] One reason for the extinction of the language was movement of the population.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] The evacuation of nearly all indigenous Auregnais to the British mainland during World War II (the island was occupied by the Wehrmacht) was thought to be a major factor in the final loss of the spoken language.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] Another reason for the language's demise was official neglect, especially in the education sector, where it was not taught at all.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] This led to a situation in which, as was noted by the Guernsey newspaper *Le Bailliage* in 1880, children had ceased to speak the language among themselves – partly due to teachers discouraging its use in favour of standard French.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] Along with the decline in Auregnais went the decline in the use of French.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] French ceased to be an official language in the island in 1966.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] The official French used in the Channel Islands (see Jersey Legal French) differs slightly from Metropolitan French and greatly from the vernacular Norman.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] Traces of the language still exist in many, if not most, local placenames.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] Many of these have been gallicised, but some notable examples include Ortac (Or'tac), Burhou (with the *-hou* suffix) and the first element of the name "*Braye* Harbour".
[src:auregnais/auregnais] One or two words linger on in the local English, e.g.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] *vraic* (seaweed fertiliser – a word common throughout the Channel Islands), and the pronunciation of certain local surnames, e.g.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] Dupont and Simon as [dipõ] and [symõ] rather than the standard Parisian pronunciation.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] Unusually, for such a small dialect, Auregnais used to have an exclave or "colony" of speakers on Les Casquets for a number of years.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] Algernon Charles Swinburne based his poem "Les Casquets" on the Houguez family who actually lived on the islands for 18 years.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] The Houguez family came from Alderney, and the evidence points to its members being Auregnais speakers; in fact, the daughter married a man from Alderney.
[src:auregnais/auregnais] During this time, they were isolated and would have had few visitors, but would have spoken Auregnais most of the time.
[src:auregnais/hou] Its etymology and meaning are disputed, but most specialists think it comes from Saxon or Anglo-Saxon *hōh* "heel", sometimes *hō*, then "heel-shaped promontory", "rocky steep slope", "steep shore".
[src:auregnais/hou] This toponymic appellative appears as a final *-hou* or associated with the Romance definite article *le Hou*.
[src:auregnais/hou] It can be found everywhere in Normandy, but more in the western part of it.
[src:auregnais/hou] The English toponymy uses this Saxon or Anglo-Saxon element the same way, but its result is phonetically *-hoo* or *-hoe*, sometimes *-(h)ow* or *-ho* e. g. : Northoo (Suffolk); Poddinghoo (Worcestershire); Millhoo (Essex); Fingringhoe (Essex); Rainow (Cheshire); Soho (London); etc.
[src:auregnais/hou] As an independent element it is *Hoe, Hoo, Hooe, Ho* or *the Hoe*, e.g. the Hoe at Plymouth (Dorset) above the harbour.
[src:auregnais/hou] In Normandy, it may have sometimes mixed up with Old Norse *hólmr*, meaning a small island, and often found anglicised elsewhere as "holm".
[src:auregnais/hou] It can still be found in modern Scandinavian languages, e.g.
[src:auregnais/hou] The normal evolution of *hólmr* in Normandy is *-homme*, *-houme*, even *-onne* at the end of a toponym and le Homme, le Houlme, le Hom with the article.
[src:auregnais/hou] The Norman toponym and diminutive *hommet / houmet* also derives from this element.
[src:auregnais/hou] In Parisian French, the equivalent is *îlot*, which is cognate with the English "islet".
